coachComments: M.A.P stands for Maximal Aerobic Power. It refers to the power output you can ride while at your maximal rate of oxygen consumption. These workouts include efforts that are at or just below your M.A.P.

itemName: Fitness Test: FTP and Threshold HR (50 mins)
description:
Use the results from this test to calculate your thresholds and personalise your training.
https://bit.ly/EnterBikeZones (article)

Warm Up:
15 mins in Z2,
5 mins as (15 secs in Z4 + 45 secs easy in Z2).

Main Set:
20 mins maximal steady state time trial. Go as hard as you can sustain for 20 minutes.

Warm Down:
10 mins in Z2.

Your Functional Threshold Power (FTP) is your average power for the 20-minute test multiplied by 95%.

Your Bike Threshold Heart Rate is your average for the 20-minute test less 6 beats.
coachComments:
There are TWO important steps to ensure your workouts are set at the correct level for your ability.

1/ Enter your thresholds from your fitness test results:
https://bit.ly/EnterYourThresholds (video)

2/ Use the MyProCoach auto-calculation to update your training zones: https://bit.ly/UpdateYour5TrainingZones (video)

Learn more about Bike Fitness Testing: https://bit.ly/BikeFitnessTest (article)

description:
These are workouts where the main set includes efforts that alternate above and below your one-hour threshold intensity. They are best done on an indoor trainer.

Warm Up:
15 mins in low Z2,
5 x (10 secs in Z4 + 50 secs in low Z2).

Main Set:
10 x (1 min 30 secs in Z3 + 30 secs in Z5 + 1 min in low Z2).

Warm Down:
10 mins in low Z2.

Ride mainly in Z2 today. You should be able to maintain conversation at this intensity. Don't be tempted to ride harder.

Warm Up:
20 mins in low Z2.

Main Set:
30 mins in upper Z2.

Warm Down:
10 mins in low Z2.
coachComments:
Phil's Training Tip:

Optional workouts will benefit your training but only if they are optimal to your schedule and fitness. If you can easily fit the workout into your diary without causing stress and/or fatigue then you will gain fitness.

Don't be tempted to squeeze optional workouts into a busy schedule. Save your physical and psychological energy for the next session and future training.

Warm Up:
20 mins in Z2.

Main Set:
2 x (30 mins in upper Z3 + 10 min recoveries in Z2).
20 mins in upper Z3.

Warm Down:
10 mins in low Z2.
coachComments:
Phils Training Tip:

Don't panic if you cannot complete 100% of your workouts. Do your best to stick to your plan, while accepting that occasionally life gets in the way. Following a plan will help you train more effectively than not having a plan at all. Do your best with whatever time and resources you have, and don't give up. Don't worry about one bad week, its what you do consistently over a period of months that counts.

description:
Warm Up:
20 mins in Z2.

Main Set:
2 x (40 mins in upper Z3 + 15 min recoveries in Z2).

Warm Down:
15 mins in low Z2.

Warm Up:
10 mins in Z2,
5 x (20 secs in Z3 + 40 secs in low Z2).

Main Set:
3 x (5 mins in upper Z2 + 60 sec recoveries in low Z2),
3 x (3 mins in upper Z2 + 60 sec recoveries in low Z2).

Warm Down:
10 mins in low Z2.

Aim is to accumulate a decent amount of time in and above zone 5. You will get a short 20sec rest that allows your legs to recover but your heart rate won't drop too much and then you have to go again.

The first couple of sets should be done to target power. If you feel good, you can treat the 40sec effort as a max effort to really push your body to the limit.

If you do this session on the ergo, please don't use ERG mode as the lag in resistance can be difficult and you will also limit yourself in the power range given sometimes. You are better off doing this as a free ride in level mode and producing the power yourself.

Ensure your cadence doesn't drop too much in your recovery period. Recovery cadence should be >85rpm when possible.
